# Lim Wei Meng Eugene _v_ Fan Kian Sang  

### \[2022\] SGDC 175

Tort – Assault and battery – Provocation – Contributory liability

Damages – Assessment

3 August 2022 - Judgment reserved

### District Judge Jonathan Toh Jun Hian:

## Introduction

1       The plaintiff was punched by the defendant several times and suffered various injuries to his head and face. He sued for damages for his injuries and for an adjustment disorder which required trauma-related counselling.

2       The defendant argued that he should not be liable for the plaintiff’s injuries because the “_words and actions of the Plaintiff had provoked him, triggering him to punch the Plaintiff_”.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) He also filed a counterclaim for damages on the basis that the plaintiff had retaliated by kicking the defendant after being punched, causing the defendant injury.[^2]

3       The trial proceeded solely on the plaintiff’s claim. The defendant’s counterclaim was ordered to be stayed on 16 August 2021 as the defendant failed to furnish the requisite medical report pursuant to Rules of Court (2014 Rev Ed), O 18 r 12(1A). The stay was lifted on 16 March 2022, less than a week before trial was due to start. I directed for the trial of the plaintiff’s claim to proceed first and for the defendant’s counterclaim to be tried separately as parties were ready for the trial of the plaintiff’s claim, but there was potentially a lengthy interlocutory process before the defendant’s counterclaim was ready to be tried.

4       The plaintiff’s cause of action is in the tort of battery. He must show that the defendant intentionally caused direct and unjustified physical contact with the plaintiff.[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3) The plaintiff adduced video evidence taken from his car’s front facing camera showing that the defendant had approached and verbally confronted the plaintiff, and then punched the plaintiff several times. Without more, the tort of battery appears to be made out.

5       In closing submissions, the defendant argued that he should not be liable because (a) the plaintiff provoked the defendant into a confrontation;[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4) and (b) the plaintiff re-engaged the defendant in a further confrontation when the defendant tried to leave.[^5] Alternatively, the defendant submitted that for these reasons, the plaintiff was contributorily liable for 50% of his damages.

### The legal principles relating to provocation and contributory liability in the tort of battery

6       The defendant did not cite any authorities in support of his defence arising from the plaintiff’s alleged provocation or contributory liability.

7       There is no defence of “provocation” for the tort of battery recognised in common law. However, provocation may play a part in the recognised defence of self-defence. _Per_ Lord Scott in _Ashley v Chief Constable of Sussex Police_ <span class="citation">\[2008\] 1 AC 962</span> at \[18\] (“_Ashley_”), “every person has the right also to protect himself by using reasonable force to repel an attack or prevent an imminent attack.” This included the situation where the defendant honestly and reasonably believed that he was under threat of imminent attack (_Ashley_ at \[85\]). As such, where a plaintiff’s provocative acts result in the defendant physically attacking the plaintiff out of an honest and reasonable belief that the defendant was under threat of imminent attack, it is possible for him to argue that it was done in self-defence.

8       Provocation may also play a role in other potential defences. In _Lane v Holloway_ <span class="citation">\[1968\] 1 QB 379</span> (“_Lane_”), the defendant argued that the plaintiff’s provocative acts gave rise to two defences: first, _ex turpi causa non oritur actio_ - no action could be brought for illegality since both parties were involved in an unlawful fight; and second, _volenti non fit injuria_ - both parties had voluntarily participated in the fight and therefore voluntarily took on the risk of injury (_Lane_ at 386E to 386G).

9       The facts of _Lane_ are helpful to the analysis in this case. The defendant in _Lane_ punched the plaintiff in the eye, causing serious injury. However, he was arguably provoked by the plaintiff into doing so. The plaintiff lived in a house neighbouring a café run by the defendant. They had a strained relationship due to complaints about the café and its customers. One night, the defendant’s wife and the plaintiff exchanged insults. In a confrontation between the plaintiff and the defendant, the plaintiff challenged the defendant to a fight by saying “I’ll take you on any time”.[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6) As the defendant moved toward the plaintiff, the plaintiff thought that he might be struck and threw a punch at the defendant’s shoulder. The defendant then retaliated by punching the plaintiff in the eye. The trial judge gave judgment for the plaintiff but significantly reduced damages on the basis that the plaintiff had contributed to his injury by insulting the defendant’s wife, challenging the defendant to a fight, and striking the first blow.

10     The English Court of Appeal rejected both defences on the basis that the defendant’s reaction in giving a hard punch to the plaintiff’s eye was out of all proportion to the exchange of insults, the challenge to a fight, and the plaintiff’s slight punch to the shoulder (_Lane_ at 386G to 387A).

11     On the issue of contributory liability, Lord Denning MR in _Lane_ overturned the trial judge’s holding that the plaintiff’s provocative actions operated to reduce his damages. He held that such provocation could be used to remove the element of aggravated damages, but could not reduce real damages (_Lane_ at 387G).

12     Some 10 years later, in _Murphy v Calhane_ <span class="citation">\[1977\] 1 QB 94</span>, Lord Denning MR distinguished _Lane_. He held that it was possible for a plaintiff’s conduct to be serious enough to amount to “fault” in s 1(1) of the Law Reform (Contributory Negligence) Act 1945 (c 28) (UK) such that a finding of contributory liability could be made.

13     This issue of whether the plaintiff’s provocative acts may be taken into account to find contributory liability in the tort of battery was finally settled by the English Court of Appeal in _Pritchard v Co-operative Group Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2012\] QB 320</span>. As explained in _Cavenagh Investment Pte Ltd v Kaushik Rajiv_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 2 SLR 543</span> at \[36\]:

> …the English Court of Appeal in _Pritchard v Co-operative Group Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2012\] QB 320</span> was asked to determine whether the defence in s 1(1) of the Law Reform (Contributory Negligence) Act 1945 (c 28) (UK) (“the 1945 Act”), which is _in pari materia_ with our provision, applies to the torts of assault and battery. The Court of Appeal explained (per Aikens LJ at \[61\]–\[62\]) that the purpose of the 1945 Act was to provide relief to claimants whose actions would have previously failed (because the common law incarnation of the defence was a complete defence) by allowing the courts to apportion damages. Its purpose was not to reduce damages which previously before the enactment of the statute would have been awarded. Therefore, if the common law defence did not apply to a tort pre-1945, the statutory defence would also not apply. **The Court of Appeal held that because it could find no case before 1945 which applied the defence to the intentional torts of assault and battery, the statutory defence likewise did not apply.**

> (emphasis in bold)

14     Accordingly, the following principles apply to the analysis of the defendant’s argument of provocation and contributory liability:

> (a)     First, the defendant cannot rely on the plaintiff’s alleged acts of provocation to argue contributory liability for an action in the tort of battery. This is sufficient for me to reject the defendant’s submission that the plaintiff should be contributorily liable for 50% of his own injuries.

> (b)     Second, for the defence of self-defence, the question is whether the plaintiff’s alleged acts of provocation gave the defendant an honest and reasonable belief that the defendant was under threat of imminent attack.

> (c)     Third, other potential defences such as _ex turpi causa non oritur actio_ or _volenti non fit injuria_ will not succeed if the defendant’s acts of battery is disproportionate to the plaintiff’s alleged acts of provocation.

### The alleged acts of provocation

15     The defendant alleged that the following events took place and that they were provocative:

> (a)     First, that the plaintiff had acted aggressively by initially driving up to the defendant’s car and sounding his horn loudly. After the defendant reversed to give the plaintiff space, the plaintiff again drove towards the defendant and sounded his horn. The defendant felt that this repeated and excessive sounding of the horn was provocative and dangerous.[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7)

> (b)     Second, that as the plaintiff drove past the defendant’s car, the plaintiff pointed the middle finger followed by an open palm sign which the defendant understood as the plaintiff asking the defendant to wait at that spot for the plaintiff to return to settle the dispute.[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8)

> (c)     Third, that during the confrontation between the plaintiff and the defendant on level four of the carpark, the plaintiff had a fierce expression on his face, with arms raised and showing a rude sign with a thumb showing in between his clenched fist.[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9) He then said “I don’t fuck care if your mother falls and dies”, and then applied force on the defendant’s chest and spit at the defendant, which triggered the defendant to react defensively with some punches.[^10]

16     I will address each of these allegations as I review the facts.

## The Facts

17     On 17 January 2018 at around 11 am, the plaintiff was driving home and intended to park his car at the multi-storey carpark at Block 748 Bedok Reservoir Crescent. To do so, he had to use the service road along Block 748C Bedok Reservoir Crescent, which was a single carriageway with one lane going in each direction.

18     The events leading up to the punches were captured on four video clips taken from the plaintiff’s in-car front facing camera with the time-stamps as follows:

> (a)     Video 1: 06:32:42 – 06:33:42;

> (b)     Video 2: 06:34:44 – 06:35:44;

> (c)     Video 3: 06:36:46 – 06:37:46; and

> (d)     Video 4: 06:37:47 – 06:38:47.

19     It is common ground that the time stamps on the videos do not reflect the time of the incident, which took place past 11 am on 17 January 2018.

20     As the plaintiff was driving along the service road, the defendant was parked next to Block 748C facing in the opposite direction and blocking the plaintiff’s path. A screenshot of the starting frame of Video 1 shows their respective positions.

![](data:image;base64,)

### Did the plaintiff horn repeatedly and provocatively?

21     Video 1 starts with the plaintiff sounding his horn and driving forward slowly to approach the defendant’s car parked at the position shown in the screenshot above. The defendant then reversed his car about one car length, stopped, and alighted. The plaintiff, upon seeing the defendant alight, drove around the defendant’s car by encroaching on the opposite lane and continued on towards the carpark.

22     The defendant alleged that the plaintiff had sounded his horn repeatedly and provocatively. The defendant reversed twice to give way but was pursued by the plaintiff each time.[\[note: 11\]](#Ftn_11) These events allegedly took place before the events recorded in Video 1. I did not think that this was true. At the start of Video 1, the defendant’s car already parked at the spot which, according to him, was the safest spot to wait for his elderly mother to embark.[^12] If his account of the repeated reversing and pursuit were true, the defendant had to be initially parked at a place ahead of this ideal spot. This was not borne out by his own evidence. In my view, Video 1 shows the first encounter between the plaintiff and the defendant, with the plaintiff sounding his horn and driving slowly towards the defendant. As such, I find that the plaintiff had only sounded his horn once at the defendant as reflected at the start of Video 1.

### Did the plaintiff gesture rudely while driving past the defendant?

23     The defendant also alleged that as the plaintiff drove past his car, the plaintiff pointed the middle finger followed by an open palm sign which the defendant understood as the plaintiff asking the defendant to wait at that spot for the plaintiff to return to settle the dispute.[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13) The plaintiff denied this.

24     On balance, I find that the evidence does not support the plaintiff having made these gestures while driving past the defendant’s car.

> (a)     The plaintiff explained in cross-examination that the incident happened on the first Father’s Day when he was a father, his son being just under four months old. He was on his way home after running an errand at the supermarket.[\[note: 14\]](#Ftn_14) His wife and new-born son were alone at home and he was keen to return as quickly as possible.[^15] When he saw the defendant parked on the wrong side of the road blocking his path, he experienced some frustration.[^16] However, when he saw the defendant alight from his car, he felt that there was a possibility that the defendant was looking for trouble so his instinctive reaction was to drive off.[^17] I accept his evidence that this was his state of mind at that point in time.

> (b)     A close analysis of Video 1 reveals that as the defendant alighted from his car, the plaintiff activated his signal light as a ticking sound could be heard. The plaintiff then steered his car right to enter the opposite lane. As he was passing the defendant’s car, he again activated the signal light and steered left back into the correct lane. His hands were likely to be occupied with these actions. Further, as he was steering his car onto the opposite lane, his attention would have been on the opposite lane and the potential traffic situation. This made it more likely that he did not make the alleged gestures toward the defendant.

> (c)     Finally, and most tellingly, there was a relatively long verbal exchange between the plaintiff and the defendant before the defendant threw the first punch (see below, \[28\]). During this exchange, the defendant repeatedly confronted the plaintiff about sounding his horn, but said nothing about the alleged rude gestures or his alleged perception that the plaintiff had asked the defendant to wait for him to return to settle the dispute. This contradicted the defendant’s explanation that he went in search of the plaintiff because he was mainly worried about the gesture showing the plaintiff’s intention to return to confront him, which could mean trouble for his wife or mother.[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18) If this explanation was true, I would have expected the defendant to have confronted the plaintiff about the gestures, but he did not. He only complained about the horn.

25     Given these three points, I find on balance that the plaintiff did not make the rude gestures with his hands when driving past the defendant.

26     After entering the carpark, the plaintiff drove up to level four of the multi-storey carpark to park his car. While there was a time gap between Video 1 and Video 2, nothing turns on this. The defendant did not allege that anything significant happened during the time period.

### The confrontation on level four of the carpark

27     While the plaintiff was parking his car, the defendant was searching for him across seven lower carpark decks. There is another gap of about one minute between Videos 3 and 4 when this was occurring. Again, nothing turns on this gap as there is no allegation that anything significant happened during this time. The defendant submitted that it was suspicious that the plaintiff spent such a long time sitting in his car and suggested that the plaintiff was setting a trap to capture the defendant attacking the plaintiff on video. I did not agree with this suggestion. If the plaintiff had intended to set a trap, it was a poor one. The success of this alleged “trap” was contingent on the defendant expending significant effort to search seven lower carpark decks to find the plaintiff.

28     Videos 3 and 4 capture the confrontation between the parties prior to the first punch from the defendant. It is worth setting out the video time stamps of the specific exchange of words that I observed on the videos.

29     At the end of this last sentence, at timestamp 06:38:34 of Video 4, the defendant threw a punch connecting with the right side of the plaintiff’s head while shouting a Hokkien vulgarity. The defendant then threw four more consecutive punches with both fists, hurling vulgarities with each punch. The plaintiff stumbled out of the frame of the video on the right side of the car.

### The alleged acts of provocation during the confrontation

30     I first deal with the allegation that the plaintiff had a fierce look on his face “as if spoiling for a fight”.[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19) It would not be a surprise if the plaintiff looked unhappy given that he was being confronted by the defendant. However, I did not think that the plaintiff looked like he was spoiling for a fight. The plaintiff’s conduct during the entire confrontation was relatively neutral. He did not use any vulgarities and his gestures as captured on video were measured.

31     As for the allegation that the plaintiff showed a rude sign with a thumb showing in between his clenched fist, the defendant did not explain what he understood this sign to mean and why such a sign was offensive to him. No such sign could be seen in Video 4. Although there were brief moments where the plaintiff’s right hand was obscured from view, I did not think that he was showing a rude sign to the defendant in those moments. As mentioned, the plaintiff’s conduct was relatively neutral throughout the confrontation, and it was the defendant who was the aggressor. There was also no specific reaction from the defendant reflecting that he thought that the plaintiff had showed him a rude sign.

32     I also find that the plaintiff did not say the words “I don’t fuck care if your mother falls and dies” or something to that effect as alleged.

> (a)     First, it is not captured on the video. While there were several responses from the plaintiff that were not audible, none of the defendant’s reactions to these inaudible responses remotely suggested that the plaintiff had spoken such incendiary words.

> (b)     Second, the defendant’s initial account as set out in written representations to the public prosecutor dated 16 January 2019 at \[4(p)\] to \[4(r)\] was that the defendant had explained to the plaintiff that he was simply waiting at the particular spot for his mother who was 95 years old, to which the plaintiff responded with these provocative words.[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20) However, the video does not record the defendant giving such an explanation to the plaintiff. Rather, the defendant simply said “Yeah I’m fetching an elderly. So what?”. It would be unnatural for the plaintiff to immediately assume that this elderly person is the defendant’s mother, and further proceed to curse her. This allegation appears to have been earlier advanced in the defendant’s representations based on the defendant’s memory before he had the chance to review Video 4 carefully. However, there is no substance to the allegation, and it should have been retracted after the defendant had a chance to review Video 4.

33     I move on to the allegation that the plaintiff spit at the defendant and applied force to the defendant’s chest, which triggered the defendant to punch the plaintiff. The defendant’s initial account in his AEIC was that the plaintiff first spit at him. After that, the defendant felt a force on his chest which triggered him to issue the punch.[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21) In cross-examination, he changed the sequence of events and insisted that it was the spit that triggered him to punch the plaintiff.[^22] I find that neither of these alleged acts took place as the video does not show them.

> (a)     In relation to the force, the defendant’s evidence in cross-examination was that the plaintiff did so at the 28 second mark of Video 4,[\[note: 23\]](#Ftn_23) which would bear the timestamp 06:38:16. While the plaintiff’s right hand is obscured by his body, there was no discernible reaction from the defendant to suggest that there was physical contact at this point in time. I find that the plaintiff did not touch the defendant at this time.

> (b)     I move on to the alleged spit. Right before he was punched, the plaintiff said the words “If I want, I would have talked to you in person. I don’t want to talk to you that much.” The defendant’s evidence in cross-examination was that while the plaintiff spit at him while saying the words “I don’t want to talk to you that much”.[\[note: 24\]](#Ftn_24) I could not accept this. There was no pause in the sentence where the plaintiff could possibly have spat at the defendant. The moment the plaintiff completed speaking the word “much”, he was punched in the head. There was simply no opportunity for the alleged spitting to have taken place.

34     In these circumstances, I find that the plaintiff neither applied force to the defendant’s chest nor spat at the defendant during the confrontation.

35     After the defendant punched the plaintiff five times, the plaintiff stumbled backwards out of the frame of the video towards the right side of the car. The defendant is seen adjusting his watch and stalking out of the frame towards the plaintiff while continuing to speak a Hokkien vulgar phrase followed by the words “ah, think what…. Ah”. A sound of pain from the plaintiff is heard at the end of the video.

## My findings on the alleged provocation

36     Given the facts set out above, it was clear to me that the plaintiff did not provoke the defendant into a confrontation. On the contrary, the plaintiff tried to avoid a confrontation.

37     First, as the plaintiff was driving towards the defendant’s car parked beside Block 748C Bedok Reservoir Crescent, he did sound his horn at the defendant. When the defendant reversed, the plaintiff did move forward in tandem. However, when the defendant alighted from the car, the plaintiff immediately drove around the defendant and went into the carpark. I also repeat the finding at \[24\] – \[25\] above that the plaintiff did not make the alleged rude gestures while driving past the defendant. This indicated to me that the plaintiff intended to avoid any confrontation with the defendant.

38     Second, Video 1 at timestamp 06:33:18 showed the plaintiff muttering to himself in mandarin while driving in the carpark after passing the defendant who had alighted. While no translation of this was presented in evidence, the defendant submitted that this should be translated to mean “what’s the point of speaking so much dickhead language? Do you think I have time to speak… what a waste of time and energy to speak!”.[\[note: 25\]](#Ftn_25) In my view, this meant that the plaintiff did not want to have a confrontation with the defendant and chose to drive away because the plaintiff viewed it as a waste of his time.

39     Third, the plaintiff had driven all the way to level four of the carpark to park his car. As such, it required a great deal of effort for the defendant to follow the plaintiff on foot. His evidence was that he had lost sight of the plaintiff’s car and searched seven lower decks before finding the plaintiff. By that time, he was panting badly.[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26) This showed that the defendant was determined to seek out the plaintiff to confront him. The plaintiff had, whether intentionally or not, made himself difficult to find. This also puts paid to the suggestion that the plaintiff was setting up a trap for the defendant.

40     Fourth, the only provocation prior to the confrontation was that the plaintiff had sounded his horn once at the defendant. This was the only matter on the defendant’s mind during the confrontation as it was the only matter raised by him. This did not come close to justifying the defendant’s act of seeking the plaintiff out, confronting him, punching him and causing him serious injury.

41     In summary, I saw nothing about the plaintiff’s conduct throughout the incident that would justify the defendant’s actions. The fault lay entirely with the defendant. In the face of the defendant’s rude and aggressive behaviour, the plaintiff maintained relative composure and was in the midst of informing the defendant that he did not want to have a confrontation just before he was punched.

42     In the circumstances, the defendant’s alleged defence that he was provoked into punching the plaintiff fails in its entirety.

## Other issues

### The defendant’s allegation that the plaintiff kicked him twice

43     The defendant alleges that after the events captured on Video 4, the plaintiff kicked him twice.

> (a)     First, after the parties moved to the right side of the car, the plaintiff kicked the defendant in the left calf.[\[note: 27\]](#Ftn_27)

> (b)     Second, after this kick, the defendant tried to disengage and run away. The plaintiff then chased after him, caught him, and kicked him again on his left calf.[\[note: 28\]](#Ftn_28)

44     These allegations constitute the substance of the defendant’s counterclaim. They do not form a defence against the plaintiff’s claim as they occurred after the defendant punched the plaintiff. As the defendant’s counterclaim will be tried separately, I will say no more on these allegations.

### The relevance of the defendant’s criminal conviction

45     The defendant was charged with an offence under Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed), s 325. He pleaded guilty and accepted the Prosecution’s statement of facts. Pursuant to Evidence Act 1893 (2020 Rev Ed), s 45A, the fact of the defendant’s conviction was relevant and admissible.

46     Parties submitted on the effect of the defendant’s conviction. The plaintiff sought to rely on it to bolster his case and the defendant sought to distance himself from it by arguing that his personal circumstances had prompted him to plead guilty and accept the statement of facts despite his reservations. Nothing really turned on these arguments. This was a case where the plaintiff had adduced the requisite evidence to prove his case, and I did not think that the defendant’s conviction had much effect on the analysis of the evidence leading to my findings of fact set out above.

## The injuries caused by the defendant’s battery

47     An unidentified Indian gentleman intervened between the parties and the defendant left the scene. After he left, the Indian gentleman called the police and the plaintiff was brought to Changi General Hospital. He was hospitalised for four days from 17 June 2018 to 20 June 2018 and was given hospitalisation leave for 14 days.[\[note: 29\]](#Ftn_29) The medical report dated 3 September 2020 was prepared by Dr Yvonne Chung Hsi-Wei, a senior consultant with Changi General Hospital in the field of oculoplastics (“Dr Chung’s Report”),[^30] and noted that the plaintiff suffered the following injuries:

> (a)     A depressed fracture of the right lamina papyracea;

> (b)     An un-displaced fracture of the right orbital roof traversing the right frontal sinus anterior wall;

> (c)     Herniation of the right medial rectus;

> (d)     Swelling over the right eye; and

> (e)     A laceration over the upper eyelid on the medial aspect.

48     The defendant pleaded guilty to the charge[\[note: 31\]](#Ftn_31) stating that he had caused the plaintiff to suffer these injuries, and did not argue the contrary before me.

## Conclusion on the defendant’s liability

49     Given my factual findings above, it is clear that the defendant is wholly liable for the plaintiff’s injuries, which were caused by his punches.

50     I concluded above at \[14(a)\] that in law, the defendant cannot rely on the plaintiff’s acts of provocation to argue contributory liability for the tort of battery. After a review of the facts, I find that in any case, nothing that the plaintiff did in this case possibly justified or contributed to the wholly disproportionate physical attack on him by the defendant.

#### Head injuries and facial lacerations

53     Due to the injuries, the plaintiff had to undergo the following procedures:

> (a)     He underwent emergency surgery on 17 July 2018 of the repair of the bicanalicular laceration with silicon intubation, and repair of eyelid laceration (Dr Chung’s Report, page 1);[\[note: 32\]](#Ftn_32)

> (b)     He was hospitalised for four days and was discharged on 20 June 2018 (Dr Chung’s Report, page 2);[\[note: 33\]](#Ftn_33)

> (c)     He was reviewed on 25 June, 9 July, 13 July and 10 August 2018 and was stable at these reviews (Dr Chung’s Report, page 2);[\[note: 34\]](#Ftn_34) and

> (d)     He had the canalicular stent removed on 30 November 2018 (Dr Chung’s Report, page 2).[\[note: 35\]](#Ftn_35)

54     On his final review on 16 April 2019 by Dr Chung, it was noted that the plaintiff’s lower lid punctum and canalicular system were not functional (Dr Chung’s Report, page 3).[\[note: 36\]](#Ftn_36) Dr Chung explained in court the plaintiff’s right canicular system had been sheared in half and a stent was placed to repair it. However, after the stent was removed, scar tissue formed to render it non-functional. As a result, tears in his right eye could not drain into his throat,[^37] and he would suffer from epiphora, or symptoms of tearing, for the rest of his life unless there was further surgical intervention.

55     The plaintiff relied on the following precedents to support his claim for $5,000 for head injury:

> (a)      _Yusuf bin Darus v Singapore Bus Service_ (1978) Ltd (HC Suit No. 19 of 1997) as cited in the _Practitioners’ Library – Assessment of Damages: Personal Injuries and Fatal Accidents_ (LexisNexis, 3rd Ed, 2017) (“_Practitioners’ Library_”) at p 187). This case involved a serious injury where the plaintiff suffered fractures to the skull, frontal sinus and left orbit, as well as brain and eye injuries that led to disabilities. As part of a total award for pain and suffering of $88,000, $3,000 was awarded for the fracture of the left orbit.

> (b)      _Errol Sanath Nanayakara v Juan Badathuruge Buddilal_ (HC Suit No. 312 of 1996) as cited in _Practitioners’ Library_ at 229. Again, this case involved multiple fractures of the face including the left zygoma, medial orbital wall, left maxilla, nose, as well as multiple facial lacerations. As part of a total award for pain and suffering for head injuries of $31,000, $6,000 was awarded for the fracture of the medial orbital wall.

> (c)      _Wong Kwok Keong v Zee Lee Si_e_h (administratrix of the estate of Khong Yung Yew Aloysius, decd)_ (HC Suit No. 913 of 1999). The plaintiff suffered head injuries which included loss of consciousness (Glasgow Coma Scale 15), fracture of the left orbital floor and medial wall and left periorbital haematoma, and nasal fracture and nasoethmoid fracture. Pain and suffering for the head injuries were assessed at $14,000, with $7,500 awarded for the fracture of the left orbital floor and medial wall and left periorbital haematoma.

56     The defendant submitted that the plaintiff sustained only an “extremely minor” injury that required four stitches and therefore should only be allowed $1,000. He relied on the scale for minor head injuries from $1,000 to $6,000 found in Charlene Chee _et al_, _Guidelines for the Assessment of General Damages in Personal Injury Cases_ (Academy Publishing, 2010) (the “_Guidelines_”) at p 6 and submitted that the plaintiff’s injury was at the lowest end of the scale.[\[note: 38\]](#Ftn_38)

57     For facial lacerations, both parties relied on the same scale in the _Guidelines_ between $2,500 - $5,000.[\[note: 39\]](#Ftn_39) The guidance provided was that the award was higher “in cases where the laceration leaves a scar that cannot be completely removed by cosmetic surgery, especially where the injured person is a young female.” The defendant submitted that the lower end of the scale was applicable because the plaintiff required only four stiches.[^40]

58     I did not agree that the plaintiff’s injury was at the lowest end of the scale for minor head injuries or facial lacerations. The defendant’s submissions did not take into account the fact that the plaintiff had to undergo emergency surgery on 17 July 2018 for the repair of both the bicanalicular laceration and the eyelid laceration. He was hospitalised for four days and had to be reviewed in June, July, August, and November 2018, and a final review on April 2019. His lower lid punctum and canalicular system were permanently damaged and he would continuously suffer from epiphora which may require further surgery.

59     Given the above, I find the plaintiff’s claim for pain and suffering for $5,000 for his head injury and $3,000 for the facial lacerations eminently reasonable.

60     I further note that although the _Guidelines_ do not specifically provide a scale for fractured orbit, a total claim of $8,000 fall well within the guidelines for fractures of other parts of the face:[\[note: 41\]](#Ftn_41)

> 
| 

(a)

 | 

Fractured malar complex

 | 

$10,000 - $20,000

 |
| 

(b)

 | 

Fractured maxilla (facial bone, upper jaw)

 | 

$10,000 - $20,000

 |
| 

(c)

 | 

Fractured zygoma (cheek bone)

 | 

$6,000 - $10,000

 |

  
  

61     In the circumstances, I assess damages for the plaintiff’s head injury at $5,000 and facial lacerations at $3,000 as claimed by the plaintiff.

#### Adjustment disorder

62     After the plaintiff was treated at Changi General Hospital, he was referred for psychiatric evaluation. Dr Cheryl Loh, the Chief and Senior Consultant of the Department of Psychological Medicine of Changi General Hospital diagnosed him as having an adjustment disorder secondary to being assaulted (the “Adjustment Disorder”). She summarised his symptoms and treatment in her report dated 3 August 2020 as follows:

> He had a brief period of symptoms of anxiety, fear of being attacked, intrusive thoughts and memories of the event, and poor sleep. These gradually reduced over the next 1 month and had mostly resolved by 4-5 months. He did not require regular medication and had 2 sessions of trauma-related counselling. He was well when last reviewed on 22 March 2019.

63     The defendant rather surprisingly argued, on the authority of _Man Mohan Singh s/o Jothirambal Singh & Anor v Zurich Insurance (S) Pte Ltd (n.k.a. QBE Insurance (S) Pte Ltd) & Anor_ _<span class="citation">\[2008\] 3 SLR(R) 735</span>_, that the plaintiff had no claim for psychiatric harm because there was no legal proximity between the parties.[^42] However, the requirement of legal proximity in that case arose from a claim in the tort of negligence and has nothing to do with the present claim in the tort of battery.

64     For completeness, on the issue of causation, it was not surprising to me that the plaintiff, who had suffered verbal and physical attacks by the defendant resulting in serious injury, would also suffer psychiatric harm caused by the battery in terms of the Adjustment Disorder as diagnosed by Dr Loh.

65     The defendant did not suggest that Dr Loh’s diagnosis of an Adjustment Disorder failed to meet the requirement of a recognisable psychiatric illness, or call any expert to refute Dr Loh’s diagnosis. He submitted that the disorder was minor and warranted damages of no more than $1,000.

66     The plaintiff cited _Buy Ee Seng Jonathan v Quek Seng Huat_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGDC 187</span> for the proposition that he had suffered a “mild” case of “chronic pain syndrome”. I did not think that this was applicable. The claimant in that case complained of chronic pain that persisted for a long time beyond the expected time of recovery. This is not the case here. The plaintiff suffered from an Adjustment Disorder due to the attack that he experienced. As Dr Loh explained in cross-examination, the plaintiff initially had symptoms that suggested post-traumatic stress disorder. However, as his symptoms subsided about a month later, she diagnosed him as having an Adjustment Disorder rather than the more serious post-traumatic stress disorder.

67     In the Guidelines, the scale for a minor case of post-traumatic stress disorder where full recovery is achieved within one or two years is between $2,000 and $4,000. As the plaintiff’s Adjustment Disorder is less serious than that, I assess damages at $1,500.

#### Medical expenses of $9,046.62 allowed

69     The plaintiff produced the relevant invoices for his claim for medical expenses at Plaintiff’s AEIC, pp 22 – 40. The defendant did not object specifically to any of the claimed invoices. Instead, he relied on the fact that the plaintiff testified that his medical insurance covered most of the medical expenses,[\[note: 43\]](#Ftn_43) and cited _Lim Xueru v Lim Kai Meng_ <span class="citation">\[1992\] 3 SLR(R) 183</span> for the proposition that the defendant should not be made to compensate the plaintiff twice over for the same loss.[^44]

70     However, there is an established exception to the basic rule against double recovery where a plaintiff recovers any moneys under an insurance policy for which he paid the premiums. As the Court of Appeal in _Minichit Bunhom v Jazali bin Kastari_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 1 SLR 1037</span> explained at \[83\]:

> generally, these are not deductible from the plaintiff’s claim because “even if in the result the \[plaintiff\] may be compensated beyond his loss, he has paid for the accident insurance with his own moneys, and the fruits of this thrift and foresight should in fairness enure to his and not to the defendant’s advantage” (_McGregor on Damages_ at para 38-148).

71     The plaintiff’s evidence in court that it was _his_ insurance that covered the medical expenses was not challenged. As such, the sums paid out by the insurance are not deductible from the claim for medical expenses.

72     I allow the claim for medical expenses of $9,046.62.

#### Transport expenses of $200 allowed

73     I note that the plaintiff made at least 12 trips to Changi General Hospital to Eye clinic and the Psychological Medicine outpatient clinic and has claimed transport expenses of $200, although no invoices were adduced of such expenses.

74     The defendant did not object in his closing submission to the plaintiff’s claim for pre-trial transport expenses of $200.[\[note: 45\]](#Ftn_45) This claim for slightly more than $16 per round trip is reasonable and I allow it.

#### Loss of earnings of $5,084 disallowed

75     The plaintiff claimed for loss of earnings of $5,084 on the basis that he was on 22 days of medical leave in June 2018. His gross monthly salary was $6,933.30 and he claimed the alleged lost earnings for 22 days of medical leave.

76     However, the plaintiff described his medical leave as “paid medical leave”.[\[note: 46\]](#Ftn_46) He is an employee for a dairy company in Singapore and his payslip for June 2018[^47] does not suggest that he was not paid as a result of being on medical leave.

77     In the circumstances, the plaintiff has not established his claim for loss of earnings and I disallow it.

### Future Medical Expenses

78     The plaintiff claims for future medical expenses of $44,000 and future transport expenses of $1,700. He called two medical experts to give evidence of the potential future medical procedures.

> (a)     Dr Ng Siew Weng, a Consultant Plastic & Reconstructive Surgeon of SWENG Plastic Aesthetic and Reconstructive Surgery; and

> (b)     Dr Chung as referred to at \[47\] above.

79     Both doctors agreed that the plaintiff’s right lower lid punctum and canalicular system were not functioning due to scarring. As such, the plaintiff would suffer from frequent epiphora and be at risk of nasolacrimal infections. See Dr Chung’s Report, at p 3;[\[note: 48\]](#Ftn_48) Dr Ng’s Report dated 24 September 2020 at p 1 (“Dr Ng’s Report”).[^49]

80     There were two separate scarring problems.

81     First, Dr Ng observed that there was a satisfactorily healed scar extending from the medial aspect of the right upper eyelid to lower eyelid with lower lid scar contracture. His opinion was that if the right lower lid scar contracture continued to worsen, the plaintiff may experience sclera show associated with increased risk of dryness of the cornea (Dr Ng’s Report, p 2).[\[note: 50\]](#Ftn_50)

82     Dr Ng’s proposed solution was a “right lower lid scar revision with lateral canthopexy keep-in-view right lower lid local advancement flap reconstruction for wound closure. Fat grafting to right lower lid may be needed in future further (sic) improve any contour irregularity” (the “**Scar Revision Surgery**”). He estimated that the cost of this surgery will be $25,000 to $30,000, with regular post-operative follow up sessions of the next 8 to 12 months. He also stated that “the proposed treatment will help to improve patient’s current condition but he may require future surgery to improve symptoms of epiphora and follow up for nasolacrimal problems.”[\[note: 51\]](#Ftn_51)

83     The plaintiff’s lower lid scar contracture, however, was not the only problem. As Dr Chung explained, the shear injury to the plaintiff’s canalicular system was at a deeper level.[\[note: 52\]](#Ftn_52) When the plaintiff was punched, the tear drainage tube at the medial aspect of his right eye was sheared off. A stent was placed to connect the sheared tear drainage tube.[^53] However, when the stent was removed, the sheared tube did not join up but was instead taken over by the scar tissue.[^54]

84     Dr Ng’s Scar Revision Surgery targeted the visible scar at the skin level,[\[note: 55\]](#Ftn_55) but this would not address the fact that the canalicular system was no longer functioning. Dr Chung explained that the solution for the non-functional canalicular system was a dacryocystorhinostomy surgery with Jones tube which would then allow for tear drainage (the “Dacryocystorhinostomy Surgery”). However, if the Jones tube was inserted, the plaintiff would require frequent six monthly maintenance to ensure its patency and position in the nose. There was also the risk of infection. Further, if the tube was dislodged or had to be repositioned, further surgery was required. See Dr Chung’s Report at p 3.[^56]

85     The plaintiff claimed for future medical expenses for both procedures as follows:

> 
|

 |

 | 

$25,000

 |
| 

(b)

 |

 | 

$19,000

 |

broken down as follows:

86     The defendant argued that the plaintiff failed to show that these further procedures were necessary. He submitted that they appeared to be optional as the plaintiff had reasonably recovered from his injuries.[\[note: 57\]](#Ftn_57)

87     The issue before me is whether, on the balance of probabilities, these expenses will be incurred by the plaintiff in order to deal with his injuries.

#### Dacryocystorhinostomy Surgery

88     I deal first with the Dacryocystorhinostomy Surgery. Dr Chung’s report clearly states that the plaintiff suffered permanent damage to his right canalicular system with resultant frequent epiphora and risk of nasolacrimal infections. She recommended this surgery to resolve the issue. She stated there was no possibility that his injury would heal on its own without surgical intervention.[\[note: 58\]](#Ftn_58) In cross-examination, the plaintiff explained that his symptoms were getting worse[^59] but he was waiting for the outcome of the trial before proceeding with the rectification measures.[^60] I am satisfied that this procedure is necessary and that the plaintiff will likely have to incur these expenses. If the plaintiff had already undergone the procedure at the time of the trial, there was no question to my mind that he would have been entitled to claim the expenses for this procedure.

89     Dr Chung’s estimates for this surgery are found in her letter of 16 September 2020 as follows:[\[note: 61\]](#Ftn_61)

 |

#### Scar Revision Surgery

91     As for Dr Ng’s Scar Revision Surgery, the necessity of this procedure depended on whether the plaintiff’s scar contracture continued to worsen. Dr Ng’s physical examination of the plaintiff on 3 July 2020 concluded that his scar was “satisfactorily healed” but there “was a small segment of scar contracture… with an adjacent small soft tissue bulge”.[\[note: 62\]](#Ftn_62) He explained in cross examination that this did not mean that the scar was doing well. In medical terms, if a scar was healed properly, it was a “well-healed” scar. A “satisfactorily healed” scar was not well healed, although it was passable.[^63] In Dr Ng’s report under the header “Further Treatment”, he stated that “If patient’s right lower lid scar contracture continues to worsen, he may experience scelera show associated with increased risk of dryness of the cornea”. He recommended the procedure to be performed at that stage.

92     As to the question of whether the plaintiff’s right lower lid scar had continued to worsened. Dr Ng explained in court that since his last examination of the plaintiff on 3 July 2020 that it had worsened:[\[note: 64\]](#Ftn_64)

> 2 years has passed since he has seen me. Definitely the scar didn’t really behave as well, alright? And I’ve seen him just now, it appears a little bit worse than before. It remains to be seen whether it will progressively get worse until a point it is so uncomfortable that he will subject himself to a bigger procedure like what I’ve described.

93     In response to the court’s question of whether the plaintiff would need the surgery, Dr Ng further explained:

> So to answer that, I would say that I can only see over the last 2 years the scar \[h\]as worsen a bit---how much discomfort it caused him to motivate him to undertake this type of surgery is frankly to be decided by the patient, just to be very fair yah. But of course, situations whereby doctors kind of like step in to highly advise surgery would be number one, we see that a lower lid is truly pulled down and a white is shown. We see that the conjunctiva, that means the white of the eye is perpetually red due to dryness problem, okay, alright? Or on clinical examination, we definitely see the patient having a lot of tearing problem, spontaneously, then those will be the situation whereby we definitely say, you definitely need the op right now, yah.

> …

> at this point in time, okay? My take is we need to watch very closely to see whether the scar will develop any further. It will be probably---it’s still a bit early to tell because at a 2- year-mark, we see scarring now at almost the 4-year-mark, the scarring is a bit worse. So, I do not know whether at the 5th or 6th year mark, how would be, I’m not certain yah.

94     On the balance of probabilities, I find that the plaintiff’s scar contracture would likely continue to worsen and he would eventually require the Scar Revision Surgery. In particular, Dr Ng’s evidence was that the plaintiff’s scar contracture had continued to worsen in the two years since he last examined the plaintiff on 3 July 2020. The plaintiff also explained in cross-examination that his symptoms were progressively worsening.[\[note: 65\]](#Ftn_65) As such, I am of the view that the plaintiff would likely have to incur the expenses for the Scar Revision Surgery.

95     In the circumstances, I allow the Plaintiff’s claim for $25,000 for this surgery based on the lower end of Dr Ng’s estimate.

96     The plaintiff submitted that he would have to make 80 trips to Changi General Hospital (based on follow ups every six months for the next 40 years) and five trips to SWENG Plastic Aesthetic and Reconstructive Surgery and sought for an order for $1,700 to account for these transportation costs on the basis that each round trip would cost $20. As I have found that these medical procedures are likely to be necessary, I also allow the claim for future transport expenses associated with these future medical expenses.
